const boardRect = gameBoard.getBoundingClientRect(); const columnWidth = gameBoard.offsetWidth / boardWidth; const columnIndex = Math.floor((event.clientX - boardRect.left) / columnWidth); // Calculate the left position based on the column index const leftPosition = boardRect.left + columnIndex * columnWidth; draggedRectangles.forEach((draggedRectangle) => { draggedRectangle.style.left = leftPosition + 'px'; draggedRectangle.style.top = event.clientY - draggedRectangle.offsetHeight / 2 + 'px'; }); } } \`\`\` This function calculates the column index based on the current mouse position and adjusts the left position of the dragged rectangles to be aligned with that column."},{"prompt":"Write code for below STM32L432KC programming work instructions MCU: STM32L432KC Generate SCLK and CS pulse (SPI protocol) to align with incoming data stream. The incoming data will range from ~8 - 16 Mbps. The incoming data is made up of 32, 16-bit samples in a cycle, followed by 3 sync pulses shown below. The samples would eventually be scaled up to 64 samples per cycle. The sync pulses are just three successive 16-bit samples with a value of â€œ1â€ or â€œ0000000000000001â€. Steps: â€¢ Detect incoming data and sync pulses (e.g. sampling rate, timings) â€¢ Generate CS and SCLK according to above so it aligns with sync pulses (timings below) â€¢ Test and verify by sending dummy data to input pin (ideally to pin PA15) 1 cycle: 32, 16-bit samples at 30 kS/s Timing between the sync pulses (rising edge to rising edge). For 32 channels at 30 kS/s this is ~959 ns. E.g. for half the sampling rate (15 kS/s) this would be twice the length at ~1.918 us. For 32 channels at 30 kS/s the STM32L432KC generates SCLK signals with ~293 ns gaps between the 16 pulse SCLK trains, with each pulse having a length of ~20.8 ns. This will change for different channel counts and sampling rates. Align the last rising edge of the generated SCLK pulse train to have an offset in the range of ~10.4 â€“ 20.8 ns from the